ndicators mw-body-content\">\n\t</div>\n\t<h1 id=\"firstHeading\" class=\"firstHeading\" lang=\"en\">Anthimus of Nicomedia</h1>\n\t<div id=\"bodyContent\" class=\"mw-body-content\">\n\t\t<div id=\"siteSub\" class=\"noprint\">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>\n\t\t<div id=\"contentSub\"></div>\n\t\t<div id=\"contentSub2\"></div>\n\t\t\n\t\t<div id=\"jump-to-nav\"></div>\n\t\t<a class=\"mw-jump-link\" href=\"#mw-head\">Jump to navigation</a>\n\t\t<a class=\"mw-jump-link\" href=\"#searchInput\">Jump to search</a>\n\t\t<div id=\"mw-content-text\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\" class=\"mw-content-ltr\"><div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"infobox vcard\" style=\"width:22em\"><tbody><tr><th colspan=\"2\" class=\"n\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold;background-color:gold;\"><div style=\"display:inline;\" class=\"fn\">Saint Anthimus of Nicomedia</div></th></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Anthimus,_Bishop_of_Nicomedia,_and_those_with_him_(Menologion_of_Basil_II).jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Anthimus, Bishop of Nicomedia, and those with him (Menologion of Basil II).jpg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0c/Anthimus%2C_Bishop_of_Nicomedia%2C_and_those_with_him_%28Menologion_of_Basil_II%29.jpg/300px-Anthimus%2C_Bishop_of_Nicomedia%2C_and_those_with_him_%28Menologion_of_Basil_II%29.jpg\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"300\" height=\"205\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0c/Anthimus%2C_Bishop_of_Nicomedia%2C_and_those_with_him_%28Menologion_of_Basil_II%29.jpg/450px-Anthimus%2C_Bishop_of_Nicomedia%2C_and_those_with_him_%28Menologion_of_Basil_II%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0c/Anthimus%2C_Bishop_of_Nicomedia%2C_and_those_with_him_%28Menologion_of_Basil_II%29.jpg/600px-Anthimus%2C_Bishop_of_Nicomedia%2C_and_those_with_him_%28Menologion_of_Basil_II%29.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1949\" data-file-height=\"1331\" /></a><div>Miniature from the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Menologion_of_Basil_II\" title=\"Menologion of Basil II\">Menologion of Basil II</a></i></div></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Died</th><td>~303 or 311-12 AD<br />Nicomedia</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Venerated&#160;in</th><td><a href=\"/wiki/Roman_Catholic_Church\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Roman Catholic Church\">Roman Catholic Church</a>; <a href=\"/wiki/Eastern_Orthodox_Church\" title=\"Eastern Orthodox Church\">Eastern Orthodox Church</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\"><a href=\"/wiki/Calendar_of_saints\" title=\"Calendar of saints\">Feast</a></th><td>April 27; Orthodox Church: September 3</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p><b>Anthimus of Nicomedia</b> (martyred 303 or 311&#8211;12), was the <a href=\"/wiki/Bishop_of_Nicomedia\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Bishop of Nicomedia\">bishop of Nicomedia</a> in <a href=\"/wiki/Bithynia\" title=\"Bithynia\">Bithynia</a>, where he was beheaded during a <a href=\"/wiki/Persecution_of_Christians\" title=\"Persecution of Christians\">persecution of Christians</a>, traditionally placed under <a href=\"/wiki/Diocletian\" title=\"Diocletian\">Diocletian</a> (following <a href=\"/wiki/Eusebius_of_Caesarea\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Eusebius of Caesarea\">Eusebius</a>), in which \"rivers of blood\" flowed.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Anthimus_of_Nicomedia&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Nicomedia was Diocletian's chief place of residence<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> and was half-Christian, the palace itself being filled with Christians. Christian sources memorialized the \"<a href=\"/wiki/20,000_Martyrs_of_Nicomedia\" title=\"20,000 Martyrs of Nicomedia\">20,000 Martyrs of Nicomedia</a>\".  The main Christian church of Nicomedia was destroyed on February 23, 303, and the First Edict was published on the following day. Shortly after the promulgation of the edict, a fire broke out in the imperial palace; the Christians were blamed.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> The massacres transpired in the Christian communities of Bithynia after altars were set up in the marketplaces, in which no transactions were permitted until a token sacrifice to the gods and the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Daemon_(classical_mythology)\" title=\"Daemon (classical mythology)\">daemon</a></i> of the Augustus had been performed.\n</p><p>At the request of members of his congregation, Anthimus took refuge in the small village of Omana, where he provided aid to survivors<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> and sent letters exhorting the Christians to stand firm. When the soldiers of Maximinus were sent to find him, he welcomed them and fed them before revealing who he was.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> (The detail referring to Maximinus suggests that two persecutions have been <a href=\"/wiki/Conflated\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Conflated\">conflated</a>.)Amazed at his kindness, the soldiers promised him to tell Maximinus that they had not found him, but Anthimus returned with them, and converted and baptized them along the way.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> \n</p><p><a href=\"/wiki/Philip_Schaff\" title=\"Philip Schaff\">Philip Schaff</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Henry_Wace_(Anglican_priest)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Henry Wace (Anglican priest)\">Henry Wace</a> note that a fragmentary letter preserved in the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Chronicon_Paschale\" title=\"Chronicon Paschale\">Chronicon Paschale</a></i>, as written in prison by the presbyter <a href=\"/wiki/Lucian_of_Antioch\" title=\"Lucian of Antioch\">Lucian of Antioch</a> awaiting death, mentions Anthimus, bishop of Nicomedia, as having just suffered martyrdom. Schaff and Wace note that Lucian was imprisoned and put to death during the persecution of <a href=\"/wiki/Maximinus_Daia\" title=\"Maximinus Daia\">Maximinus Daia</a> (in 311 or 312) and therefore conclude that, if the fragment is genuine, Anthimus suffered martyrdom not under Diocletian but under Maximinus.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Anthimus_of_Nicomedia&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.ccel.org/ccel/schaff/npnf201.iii.xiii.vii.html\">Schaff and Wace, <i>Nicene and Post-Nicene Fathers,</i> Series II, Vol. I: Book VIII, chapter VI</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://catholicsaints.info/book-of-saints-anthimus/\">Monks of Ramsgate. \u201cAnthimus\u201d. Book of Saints, 1921. CatholicSaints.Info. 21 July 2012.</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.santiebeati.it/dettaglio/90553\">Amore, Agostino. \"Sant 'Antimo of Nicomedia\", Santi e Beati, November 19, 2001</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.greekboston.com/religion/st-anthimus-nicomedia/\">\"About Saint Anthimus of Nicomedia\", GreekBoston.com</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://oca.org/saints/lives/2013/09/03/102467-hieromartyr-anthimus-the-bishop-of-nicomedia\">\"Hieromartyr Anthimus the Bishop of Nicomedia\", Orthodox Church in America</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.goarch.org/chapel/saints?contentid=191\">\"Anthimus, Bishop of Nicomedea\", Greek Orthodox Archdiocese of America</a></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1331\nCached time: 20200813144703\nCache expiry: 2592000\nDynamic content: false\nComplications: []\nCPU time usage: 0.116 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.157 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 487/1000000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 3319/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 480/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 8/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 2509/5000000 bytes\nLua time usage: 0.044/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 1.4 MB/50 MB\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 1/400\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%  136.909      1 -total\n 47.66%   65.256      1 Template:Infobox_saint\n 38.09%   52.150      1 Template:Authority_control\n 37.30%   51.065      1 Template:Infobox\n 10.21%   13.974      4 Template:Br_separated_e